  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Through FY2026 to date, National Aeronautics and Space Administration reported total contract obligations of $9.5B across 5,863 awards with an average award size of $1.6M. Current-year totals are partial (fiscal year to date), and obligations are down 39.7% year over year. Prior fiscal-year obligations were $15B in FY21, $15.2B in FY22, $16.1B in FY23, $15B in FY24, and $15.8B in FY25, showing that FY26 to date is lower than each of the five prior full fiscal years. The largest spending by NAICS so far in FY2026 is concentrated in Research and Development in the Physical, Engineering, and Life Sciences (except Nanotechnology and Biotechnology) at $3.9B, followed by Guided Missile and Space Vehicle Manufacturing at $1.5B. Top contractors by obligations to date include CALIFORNIA INSTITUTE OF TECHNOLOGY at $1.6B and THE BOEING COMPANY at $813M, with ten vendors listed in the top-ten vendor ranking for FY2026 to date.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "How have NASA's contract obligations changed year over year?",
        "body": "Obligations are $9.5B year to date and are down 39.7% year over year. By comparison, obligations for the prior fiscal years were $15B in FY21, $15.2B in FY22, $16.1B in FY23, $15B in FY24, and $15.8B in FY25, so FY26 to date is lower than each of those years."
      },
      {
        "heading": "What are NASA buying most and who are the top vendors?",
        "body": "The largest NAICS category for FY2026 to date is Research and Development in the Physical, Engineering, and Life Sciences (except Nanotechnology and Biotechnology) at $3.9B, with Guided Missile and Space Vehicle Manufacturing next at $1.5B. The top two vendors by obligations for FY2026 to date are CALIFORNIA INSTITUTE OF TECHNOLOGY at $1.6B and THE BOEING COMPANY at $813M, with additional top-ten vendors including THE JOHNS HOPKINS UNIVERSITY APPLIED PHYSICS LABORATORY LLC at $462M and LOCKHEED MARTIN CORP at $377M."
      }
    ]
  },
